<h2>Bilingual glossary for online EC TN searches</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Understanding the Tamil and English terminology used in online EC TN records is essential for correct interpretation of the certificate data:
</p>
<ul class="guide-list" style="margin-left: 2rem; color: #475569; line-height: 1.8;">
    <li><strong>Villangam (வில்லங்கம்)</strong>: Tamil word for encumbrance. The EC is called Villangam Santhiththal.</li>
    <li><strong>Kiraiya Pattiram (கிரய பத்திரம்)</strong>: Sale Deed. Records transfer of property ownership.</li>
    <li><strong>Adhanam (அடமானம்)</strong>: Mortgage. An Adhanam deed records the pledging of property as loan collateral.</li>
    <li><strong>Vithuvidai (விடுதலை)</strong>: Release. A Vithuvidai Pattiram cancels a previously registered mortgage.</li>
    <li><strong>Pirivinai Pattiram (பிரிவினை பத்திரம்)</strong>: Partition Deed. Records legal division of jointly-owned land.</li>
    <li><strong>Patta (பட்டா)</strong>: Revenue record proving land ownership, issued by the Tahsildar office.</li>
    <li><strong>Survey Number (கணக்கு எண்)</strong>: The unique identification number for each land parcel in the revenue records.</li>
    <li><strong>SRO (Sub-Registrar Office)</strong>: The government office where all deeds are formally registered and archived.</li>
</ul>
<p class="content-text">
    After reviewing your online EC TN results, compare each deed entry against the physical copies of sale deeds and title documents. Any deed appearing in the EC that you cannot account for with a corresponding physical document requires investigation. For further guidance on interpreting EC records, visit the comprehensive <strong><a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a></strong> portal.
</p>

<h2>How to resolve mismatch in online EC TN records</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Discrepancies in the online EC TN database can occur due to data entry errors at the SRO, misspelled names, or unrecorded documents. When you identify a mistake in the digital copy, the first step is to apply for an online rectification deed or petition at the respective Sub-Registrar Office. The registration department will verify the physical registers (Book 1 and Index II) to confirm if the discrepancy is due to a transcription error. If the error is verified, the SRO updates the digital system accordingly. In cases of complex property title mismatches or missing entries of older mortgages, you may need to file a formal application with the District Registrar. Ensuring your records are clean on the <strong><a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a></strong> search database is essential before proceeding with any financial transactions or seeking banking approvals.
</p>

