<h2>What is EC Villangam online and why is it important?</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    The term Villangam translates to encumbrance or legal liability in Tamil. An encumbrance refers to any charge, lien, or claim registered against a property. E.g., when an owner takes a home loan, the bank registers a mortgage deed at the local Sub-Registrar Office (SRO). This mortgage remains active as an encumbrance until the loan is fully repaid and a mortgage release deed is registered. The <strong>ec villangam online</strong> service is the digital system that lets you search and view these transactions on the <a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a> network.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Checking the Villangam register is mandatory for multiple reasons. First, it protects you from buying a property that has been pledged as collateral for an active bank loan. Second, it helps you verify the ownership chain. The names of the sellers in the parent deeds must match the transaction logs. Third, it reveals if there are any court attachments or family partition disputes registered on the property. Performing this check via the <strong><a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a></strong> TNreginet portal ensures complete peace of mind.
</p>

