<h2>Step-by-step guide to submit an online EC application</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Follow these steps carefully to submit a successful EC application on your state portal:
</p>
<ol class="guide-list" style="margin-left: 2rem; color: #475569; line-height: 1.8;">
    <li>Open your state registration portal in a browser.</li>
    <li>Click on "Citizen Registration" if you do not have an account. Provide your name, mobile number, email ID, and Aadhaar details. Verify with OTP.</li>
    <li>Login with your new credentials.</li>
    <li>On the dashboard, look for "Encumbrance Certificate" or "EC Application" under the Citizen Services section.</li>
    <li>Select the correct Sub-Registrar Office for your property location. This is critical — selecting the wrong SRO will result in no records being found.</li>
    <li>Enter property identifiers: Village or Town name, Survey number, Subdivision number, and any applicable ward or block details.</li>
    <li>Select the search period. The start date and end date define how many years of transaction history will be covered. Banks typically require 30 years minimum.</li>
    <li>Click "Search" to preview matching records. Verify that the property details shown match your documents.</li>
    <li>Proceed to payment. Fees are calculated based on the number of years searched. Pay using net banking, UPI, or debit card through the integrated gateway.</li>
    <li>After payment, save the transaction reference number. This is your application reference ID for tracking.</li>
    <li>Monitor application status from your dashboard. Once approved, click "Download Certificate" to save the digitally signed PDF.</li>
</ol>

