<h2>Understanding Form 15 and Form 16 on Kaveri portal</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    When you request an encumbrance search online in Karnataka, the portal generates one of two forms depending on the search history. Understanding these forms is key to reading your property status correctly.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Form 15 lists all registered transactions for the selected years. It includes details such as sale deeds, mortgages, release deeds, and gift deeds, showing the parties involved and the registration dates. If your property search returns Form 15, verify each entry against your parent deeds to ensure a clean title flow.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Form 16 is issued when no registered transactions are found on the property during the search period. This is also called a Nil encumbrance certificate. Getting Form 16 indicates that the property has not been sold or mortgaged under registered deeds for those years. However, check for oral agreements or pending litigation, as they do not appear on registered forms. Combining Form 16 with a Bhoomi RTC check provides a stronger assurance of title security.
</p>

