<h2>Understanding Form 15 and Form 16 under Kerala rules</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    When you search property records in Kerala, the registration department issues one of two certificate types. Understanding the meaning of these forms helps you interpret the title search results correctly.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Form 15 is issued when the property has registered transactions during the search period. This form provides a chronological table listing the date of registration, the document number, the volume and page number, the names of the buyer and seller, and a summary of the deed. If your property search returns Form 15, inspect each entry to ensure there are no unresolved mortgages or pending partitions.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Form 16 is issued when the registration records contain no transactions for the selected years. This is commonly referred to as a Nil encumbrance certificate. Getting Form 16 shows that the property has not been sold or mortgaged under registered deeds during those years. However, a Nil certificate does not confirm physical possession or reflect oral agreements. Combining Form 16 with a physical tax receipt check is highly recommended to verify ownership status.
</p>

