<p class="content-text">
    Form 15 is issued when the property has recorded transactions during the requested period. It lists all deeds executed at the SRO including sale, mortgage, lease, power of attorney, and partition records. Each entry displays the document number, date of execution, parties involved, and the consideration amount. Banks prefer Form 15 as it provides the complete ownership history needed to assess title clarity.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Form 16 is issued when the property has no registered transactions during the requested period. This is commonly called a Nil Encumbrance Certificate. It indicates that no liabilities or transfers have been documented in the SRO registers within the chosen timeframe. Nil certificates are important during gift deed transfers, where it must be proven that the property is free from encumbrances. Checking the official <strong><a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a></strong> guides ensures you understand which form is applicable for your purpose.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Some citizens confuse the EC with a patta certificate. While the patta records ownership in revenue land records, the EC records registered transactions in the registration department. Both are required for complete title verification, but they are different documents issued by different departments. The EC focuses exclusively on registered financial and ownership transactions made at the sub-registrar office.
</p>

