<h2>Understanding the Difference: Online View vs Certified Copy</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    It is important to understand that the free search result displayed on your screen is for information purposes only. The PDF generated from the free search page is not a legally binding document. It is useful for verifying details, checking if a recent transaction has been registered, or confirming ownership details.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If you need the encumbrance certificate for official purposes, such as applying for a bank loan, submitting to a court of law, or executing a new sale deed, you must apply for a certified copy. A certified copy is officially reviewed, bears a digital signature from the Sub-Registrar, and requires payment of a government fee. You can apply for a certified copy online by logging into a registered user account on the portal and paying the required fees.
</p>

<h2>Common Discrepancies in Online EC Search Reports</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    When viewing your EC online, you might notice omissions or errors in the entries. A common issue is a transaction not appearing in the report. This can happen if the survey number was entered incorrectly during registration or if the sub-division was not recorded in the database. Another issue is the presence of an old mortgage entry that has already been paid off. If the owner did not register a release deed, the mortgage will continue to show as an active liability.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    To rectify these issues, you must contact the respective Sub-Registrar Office. If a transaction was missed due to entry errors, a correction deed or rectification request may be required. For outstanding mortgages, the borrower must obtain a discharge or release deed from the bank and get it registered at the SRO to clear the property record.
</p>

