<h2>Cross-Verifying with Meebhoomi AP Land Records</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Apart from the IGRS portal, you should cross-verify ownership records on the Meebhoomi AP website. Meebhoomi provides the Adangal (details of crops, classification, and land dimensions) and the 1B extract (revenue record of land ownership details).
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    The name of the seller on the latest registered sale deed must match the name recorded in the 1B extract. If they do not match, the seller might not have updated the revenue registers, which can block future land transactions.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    For comparison of registration systems in other states, you can visit our <strong><a href="https://econline.in/">ec online</a></strong> information pages for additional guides. Keeping up with these updates helps maintain clean and transparent titles.
</p>

<h2>Resolving Boundary and Survey Discrepancies</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Another important document is the FMB (Field Measurement Book) sketch. The FMB contains drawings showing the exact measurements of the plot. Discrepancies in the survey numbers or partition details in the sale deed can lead to boundary disputes.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If the survey details in the online EC do not match the physical documents, you must file a petition for correction. This process involves submitting parent deeds, a copy of the layout map, and requesting a physical survey by the local revenue surveyor.
</p>

<h2>Guideline Values and Tax Receipts</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Stamp duty in Andhra Pradesh is paid based on the government guideline value or the sale value, whichever is higher. Guidelines values are updated periodically by the government, and you can view them on the IGRS portal.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Additionally, ensure that the seller has paid all property taxes and utility bills up to the registration date. Receipts for these payments must be verified before completing the transaction, as unpaid dues can lead to legal recovery notices.
</p>

<h2>Zoning Regulations and Layout Approvals</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Before buying any land plot in Andhra Pradesh, verify the zoning status under local development plans. Land classification determines whether the plot is residential, commercial, industrial, or agricultural. Building on unapproved zones is illegal.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Layouts must have approvals from planning bodies like APCRDA or DTCP. Unapproved layouts are not registered under current rules, and getting building permits or electricity connections for them can be difficult.
</p>

<h2>Preventing Real Estate Scams in AP</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Fraudulent deals often involve selling a property multiple times using fake parent documents or pretending to be the owner. Always check the original deeds and request a comprehensive encumbrance certificate covering at least thirty years.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Verifying records online remains the most effective defense against fraud. It is also recommended to publish a public notice in local newspapers before signing the final sale deed, giving third parties a chance to raise any ownership claims.
</p>

<h2>Legal Implications of a Cleared Title</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    A property with a clear title guarantees that the buyer will face no legal disputes from previous owners or descendants. If a property is inherited, the buyer must check the legal heir certificate of the deceased owner. Every heir must sign the sale deed to transfer the title legally.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If any legal heir is a minor, permission from a competent court is necessary to sell their share of the property. Purchasing property without the consent of all heirs can lead to long litigation processes. This risk highlights why verifying every transaction in the encumbrance report is mandatory.
</p>

<h2>Understanding Land Types and Government Lands</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Land can be classified into private holdings and government lands. Government lands include assigned lands, forest lands, and lands reserved for public purposes. In Andhra Pradesh, assigned lands are granted to weaker sections of society for cultivation and cannot be sold to others.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If a buyer purchases assigned land, the transaction is illegal and the government can resume the land at any time without compensation. Checking the prohibited properties list on the IGRS portal is the best way to verify if a survey number is blocked for registration.
</p>';

