</p>

<h2>Resolving Survey Number Discrepancies</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Discrepancies in the survey numbers or partition details in the registered sale deed can lead to ownership disputes. To resolve these, a rectification deed must be executed. This process requires the consent of both the buyer and the seller, and it must be registered at the SRO.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If the survey details in the online EC do not match the physical documents, you must file a petition for correction. This process involves submitting parent deeds, a copy of the layout map, and requesting a physical survey by the local revenue surveyor.
</p>

<h2>Guideline Values and Tax Receipts</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Stamp duty in Tamil Nadu is paid based on the government guideline value or the sale value, whichever is higher. Guidelines values are updated periodically by the government, and you can view them on the TNReginet portal.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Additionally, ensure that the seller has paid all property taxes and utility bills up to the registration date. Receipts for these payments must be verified before completing the transaction, as unpaid dues can lead to legal recovery notices.
</p>

<h2>Zoning Regulations and Layout Approvals</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Before buying any land plot in Tamil Nadu, verify the zoning status under local development plans. Land classification determines whether the plot is residential, commercial, industrial, or agricultural. Building on unapproved zones is illegal.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Layouts must have approvals from planning bodies like DTCP or CMDA. Unapproved layouts are not registered under current rules, and getting building permits or electricity connections for them can be difficult.
</p>

<h2>Preventing Real Estate Scams</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Fraudulent deals often involve selling a property multiple times using fake parent documents or pretending to be the owner. Always check the original deeds and request a comprehensive encumbrance certificate covering at least thirty years.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Verifying records online remains the most effective defense against fraud. It is also recommended to publish a public notice in local newspapers before signing the final sale deed, giving third parties a chance to raise any ownership claims.
</p>

<h2>Legal Implications of a Cleared Title</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    A property with a clear title guarantees that the buyer will face no legal disputes from previous owners or descendants. If a property is inherited, the buyer must check the legal heir certificate of the deceased owner. Every heir must sign the sale deed to transfer the title legally.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If any legal heir is a minor, permission from a competent court is necessary to sell their share of the property. Purchasing property without the consent of all heirs can lead to long litigation processes. This risk highlights why verifying every transaction in the encumbrance report is mandatory.
</p>

<h2>Understanding Land Types and Government Lands</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Land can be classified into private holdings and government lands. Government lands include assigned lands, forest lands, and lands reserved for public purposes. In Tamil Nadu, assigned lands are granted to weaker sections of society for cultivation and cannot be sold to others.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    If a buyer purchases assigned land, the transaction is illegal and the government can resume the land at any time without compensation. Checking the prohibited properties list on the TNReginet portal is the best way to verify if a survey number is blocked for registration.
</p>

<h2>Legal Status of Agreements and Power of Attorney</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Many buyers complete transactions using sale agreements or power of attorney rather than standard sale deeds. It is vital to note that a sale agreement does not transfer title of property under registration laws. The sale remains incomplete until a sale deed is registered.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    A power of attorney must be registered at the sub-registrar office to carry legal weight. Revocation of power of attorney by the principal must also be checked, as executing a deed under a revoked power is invalid and leads to court cases.
</p>

<h2>Ensuring Proper Mutation After Registration</h2>
<p class="content-text">
    Completing deed registration at the SRO is not the final step. Buyers must complete the land mutation process to update the owner name in the revenue department files. The revenue department processes Patta mutation applications online.
</p>
<p class="content-text">
    Failing to mutate the property records can lead to situations where the previous owner name remains in the tax registers. This error allows fraudulent sellers to request duplicate deeds and try to sell the land again. Checking the revenue portal regularly confirms successful mutation.
